NEWCASTLE DISEASE - MALAYSIA: CONFIRMED
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
See Also
Newcastle disease, suspected - Malaysia: RFI 20010626.1212
Newcastle disease, suspected - Malaysia: RFI (02) 20010703.1274
Date: 26 Jul 2001
From: Jack Soo <jacksoo@kyip2asia.com>
Source: The Star newspaper, Malaysia 26 Jul 2001 [edited
<http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2001/7/26/nation/2618i
pne>

Veterinary Research Institute director Dr Aziz Jamaluddin said all the
states except Sabah and Sarawak were hit by Newcastle disease [NCD
from August last year [2000 to January [2001, adding the sickness
was still prevalent in some states.
"There is no cause for alarm. It is safe to consume chicken," he told
reporters during the regional conference on the latest advances in
diagnosis and control of Newcastle disease in poultry organized by the
institute in Ipoh on Wednesday.
The seminar was opened by Veterinary Services Department deputy
director-general Dr Matta Abdul Rahman. Dr Aziz said the conference
was held to instill awareness among breeders of the need to vaccinate
their poultry.
He said the problem of the disease started in August last year [2000,
but breeders did not inform the Government, the Department, or a
private veterinarian. "They tried to settle it on their own because
they were worried the Government would close down their farms. They
tried to absorb the losses as far as they could until 58 000 chickens
in a farm in Johor died in September last year. They knew then they
could not hold back anymore as the virus could spread to other farms,"
he said.
He said the virus here was different from the one in Australia, which
had mutated and become more aggressive than its original form. "The
difference in Asia is we do not have a critical mutation. The main
problem is vaccination is not carried out efficiently and people have
been compromising on rules. Vaccination is only being carried out at
big farms but not on chicken reared in villages," he added.
Dr Aziz said there was a need to improve building structures to
prevent birds from spreading the virus. He said poultry that had been
attacked by the disease would have symptoms such as respiratory
problems like coughing, and paralysis.
He said all poultry farmers must use the vaccine, adding there were
now about 10 local and foreign vaccines available.
